# Quality standards

Canonical source: `playbooks/standards.md`. This rule file is a thin pointer — the playbook is the source of truth and MUST be regenerated from if standards change.

## Code quality (always)

- Errors MUST be handled explicitly at every level; MUST NOT be silently swallowed
- Input crossing a trust boundary MUST be validated before processing
- Identifiers MUST be descriptive, consistent, and unambiguous; MUST match the canonical Naming Table
- Functions SHOULD be under 50 lines; files SHOULD be under 800 lines; nesting SHOULD NOT exceed 4 levels
- Comments SHOULD explain WHY only when not obvious from code; MUST NOT restate WHAT; stale comments MUST be removed
- Constants, configuration, or environment variables MUST be used for anything that could change or carries semantic meaning
- Resource cleanup MUST happen in all exit paths, including error paths
- Code MUST NOT introduce O(n²) or worse complexity on user-controlled input sizes

## Testing (mandatory for non-trivial projects)

- Line coverage minimum: 80% (95% for paths crossing trust boundaries — authentication, authorization, payment, data mutation, secret handling)
- **Test pyramid** (default, D-10 MAY override): 70% unit, 20% integration, 10% e2e
- **Per-layer coverage** (not blended): unit ≥ 80%, integration ≥ 70%, e2e ≥ critical-flow count
- TDD workflow default: failing test → minimal implementation → refactor
- Tests MUST verify behavior described in specifications, not implementation details
- Tests MUST be isolated (no shared mutable state, no execution-order dependency)
- Every test MUST cite the path-qualified `specs/<spec>.md:SC-{n}` or `specs/<spec>.md:FR-{n}` it validates (`covers_specs_auth_md_SC_3`-style suffix or in-file `Covers:` comment; commit trailers are optional metadata only)
- Deterministic test data: factories, fixtures, or seeded generators; tests MUST NOT depend on production data or unseeded randomness
- Every bug fix MUST include a test that reproduces the bug before the fix

## Contract formats (cross-trust-boundary interfaces)

- Canonical Contract Formats menu lives in `playbooks/standards.md` § Contract Formats. Use that section for the allowed machine-readable forms and the internal-only `schema: N/A — internal only` rule.

## Accessibility testing (when UI is present)

- Automated scans (axe-core / pa11y for web; platform-native linters for mobile/desktop) on every PR affecting UI code; MUST be blocking in CI
- Manual screen-reader audit cadence declared in D-13+ Accessibility Model
- Keyboard-only navigation + reduced-motion checks as part of the Verification Sequence
- Assistive-technology target declared and testable

## Security (MUST verify every applicable item before any commit)

- No hardcoded secrets (API keys, passwords, tokens, certificates, private keys) — secrets MUST be referenced by name
- No weak crypto (MD5, SHA1 for security, ECB mode, static IVs); current standards MUST be used
- Parameterized queries only — no string concatenation in SQL
- All user input validated and sanitized
- CSRF protection on state-changing operations; rate limiting on public-facing endpoints
- No PII or secrets in logs, error messages, or debug output
- Error responses MUST NOT expose internal details, stack traces, or infrastructure information
- Dependencies checked for known vulnerabilities; lockfile integrity verified
- Prototype-polluting patterns MUST be avoided in object merging / deep cloning / query parameter parsing

See `playbooks/standards.md` for the full 18-item security checklist with mechanical/judgment tags.

## Scope and minimum bar

These standards are the **minimum acceptable quality bar**, not the target. Thoroughness in every step prevents costly rework. Floors like "<50 lines" or "80% coverage" MUST be treated as floors — higher quality is pursued when the situation warrants it.

## Self-review before every commit

The Self-Review Checklist in `playbooks/standards.md` MUST pass before any code change is marked complete. For items that can be machine-verified, the agent MUST record actual command output as evidence and MUST NOT check items from memory.
